    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>How to Identify a Font by Its Visual Features</h2>
      <p>Identifying a font doesn't always require image recognition or expensive tools. By examining a font's <strong>visual characteristics</strong> — its serifs, stroke weight, x-height, and letter shapes — you can narrow down the typeface to a handful of likely matches. This <strong>font identifier</strong> walks you through that process step by step.</p>

      <h3>Key Characteristics to Look For</h3>
      <p><strong>Serifs vs. sans-serifs</strong> is the most obvious starting point. Serifs are the small decorative strokes at the ends of letters — fonts like Times New Roman and Georgia have them, while Arial and Helvetica don't. Beyond that, examine the <strong>stroke contrast</strong> (the difference between thick and thin parts of letters), <strong>x-height</strong> (the height of lowercase letters relative to uppercase), and <strong>letter shape</strong> (are the curves geometric and circular, or humanist and organic?).</p>

      <h3>Using the Font Comparison Mode</h3>
      <p>Once you have a few candidate fonts, use the <strong>font comparison mode</strong> to see them side by side with your own sample text. Pay attention to subtle differences in letterforms, spacing, and overall texture. This is especially helpful when choosing between visually similar fonts like Helvetica and Arial, or Georgia and Times New Roman.</p>

      <h3>Tips for Better Results</h3>
      <p>Focus on distinctive letterforms when identifying fonts. The lowercase <strong>a</strong> (single vs. double story), the uppercase <strong>Q</strong> (tail style), the lowercase <strong>g</strong> (single vs. double story), and the shape of terminals on letters like <strong>c</strong> and <strong>e</strong> are often the most telling features. The more questions you answer accurately, the better your matches will be.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How does the font identifier work?</h3>
        <p>The font identifier uses a guided questionnaire that asks about visual characteristics of the font you're trying to identify — such as whether it has serifs, its stroke weight, x-height, letter shapes, and overall style. Based on your answers, it narrows down matches from a curated database of 50+ popular Google Fonts and system fonts, showing live previews of each match.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I compare fonts side by side?</h3>
        <p>Yes. The font comparison mode lets you type custom text and see it rendered in up to three fonts simultaneously. This makes it easy to spot subtle differences between similar typefaces and pick the one that best matches the font you're trying to identify.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What fonts are included in the database?</h3>
        <p>The database includes over 50 popular fonts from Google Fonts and common system fonts. It covers a wide range of categories including serif, sans-serif, monospace, display, and handwriting fonts. Each font is tagged with visual characteristics like stroke contrast, x-height, letter roundness, and more.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is this tool free to use?</h3>
        <p>Yes, the font identifier is completely free. It runs entirely in your browser with no uploads, no sign-ups, and no limits. Font previews are loaded from Google Fonts, which is also free for both personal and commercial use.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What if the font I'm looking for isn't in the results?</h3>
        <p>If your exact font isn't in the database, the tool will still show the closest matches based on the visual characteristics you described. These similar fonts can serve as alternatives or help you refine your search. You can also use the comparison mode to test different fonts against each other until you find the best match.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

